State mutation happens when you try to update the state of a component without actually using setState function. This can happen when you are trying to do some computations using a state variable and unknowingly save the result in the same state variable. This is the main reason why it is advised to return new instances of state variables from the reducers by using Object.assign({}, ...) or spread syntax.This can cause unknown issues in the UI as the value of the state variable got updated without telling React to check what all components were being affected from this update and it can cause UI bugs.Ex:```javascript
 class A extends React.component {
   constructor(props) {
     super(props);
     this.state = {
